The FLC-based synchronization technique is faster than the PLL-based technique resulting in an increase in the delivered electrical energy to the grid in dynamic states, especially for the big phase error. It can be concluded that in dynamic states the PV system synchronized by FLC method can deliver more energy to the grid than the standard PV system with the PLL-based synchronization strategy. In order to compare and show the energy efficiency of the investigated cases during dynamic state, the percentage energy coefficient ΔE was defined as follows:1ΔE=(ΔEFLC-ΔEPLL)100%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta E = (\Delta E_{\text{FLC}} - \Delta E_{\text{PLL}} )100\%$$\end{document}where ΔEFLC and ΔEPLL are the measured energy delivered to the grid from the time of the dynamic state beginning to the 110% of the maximum response time for FLC-based and PLL-based method, respectively.
